# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a90-road
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The **A1**, also known as the **Great North Road**, is the longest numbered road in the United Kingdom, at 410 miles (660 km).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It connects London, the capital of England, with Edinburgh, the capital of Scotland.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The numbering system for A-roads, devised in the early 1920s, was based around patterns of roads radiating from two hubs at London and Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The first number in the system, A1, was given to the most important part of that system: the road from London to Edinburgh, joining the two central points of the system and linking two of the UK's mainland capital cities.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It was designated by the Ministry of Transport in 1921, and for much of its route it followed various branches of the historic Great North Road, the main deviation being between Boroughbridge and Darlington.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The course of the A1 has changed where towns or villages have been bypassed, and where new alignments have taken a slightly different route.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Between the North Circular Road in London and Morpeth in Northumberland, the road is a dual carriageway, several sections of which have been upgraded to motorway standard and designated A1(M).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Between the M25 (near London) and the A720 (near Edinburgh) the road is part of the unsigned Euroroute E15 from Inverness to Algeciras.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 is the latest in a series of routes north from London to York and beyond.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It was designated in 1921 by the Ministry of Transport under the Great Britain road numbering scheme.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The earliest documented northern routes are the roads created by the Romans during the period from AD 43 to AD 410, which consisted of several *itinera* (plural of *iter*) recorded in the Antonine Itinerary.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A combination of these were used by the Anglo-Saxons as the route from London to York, and together became known as Ermine Street.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Ermine Street later became known as the Old North Road.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Part of this route in London is followed by the current A10.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] By the 12th century, because of flooding and damage by traffic, an alternative route out of London was found through Muswell Hill, and became part of the Great North Road.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A turnpike road, New North Road and Canonbury Road (A1200 road), was constructed in 1812 linking the start of the Old North Road around Shoreditch with the Great North Road at Highbury Corner.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] While the route of the A1 outside London mainly follows the Great North Road route used by mail coaches between London and Edinburgh, within London the coaching route is only followed through Islington.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A number of bypasses were built from 1926 onwards, including around Barnet and Hatfield in 1927, but it was not until c.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Chester-le-Street bypass, opened in 1931, was the first bypass to be built as a dual carriageway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 1960 Stamford, Biggleswade and Doncaster were bypassed, as was Retford in 1961.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Baldock, Eaton Socon and Buckden were bypassed in 1967.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] During the early 1970s plans to widen the A1 along Archway Road in London were abandoned after considerable opposition and four public inquiries during which road protesters disrupted proceedings.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Hatfield cut-and-cover was opened in 1986.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A proposal to upgrade the whole of the A1 to motorway status was investigated by the government in 1989 but was dropped in 1995, along with many other schemes, in response to road protests against other road schemes (including the Newbury Bypass and the M3 extension through Twyford Down).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The inns on the road, many of which still survive, were staging posts on the coach routes, providing accommodation, stabling for the horses and replacement mounts.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Few of the surviving coaching inns can be seen while driving on the A1, because the modern route now bypasses the towns with the inns.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 runs from outside St Paul's tube station in the City of London near St.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Paul's Cathedral to Edinburgh Waverley railway station in the centre of the Scottish capital.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It shares its London terminus with the A40 and A1211 roads at the Museum of London Rotunda.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Martin's Le Grand and Aldersgate Street, through Islington (where Goswell Road and Upper Street form part of its route), up Holloway Road, through Highgate, Mill Hill, and Barnet where it has its last at-grade roundabout for 37 miles at Stirling Corner.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The road enters Hertfordshire just before Potters Bar, near the junction with the M25 at the South Mimms Services.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The route here becomes the A1(M) and subsequently passes underneath Hatfield, and by Welwyn, Stevenage, and Baldock.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] But it once again becomes a dual carriageway with some at-grade junctions from Baldock Junction 10, past Biggleswade, Sandy and several small villages including the ‘Black Cat’ roundabout to Buckden, then on to Alconbury and the A1(M) at Junction 14.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Junctions 11, 12 and 13 (for a motorway-standard road) may not be built until upgrading of the A1 here to a motorway is approved (possibly when the planned New Town at Tempsford is commenced).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Scotch Corner, in North Yorkshire, marks the point where, before the M6 was built, the traffic for Glasgow and the west of Scotland diverged from that for Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] As well as a hotel there have been a variety of sites for the transport café, now subsumed as a motorway services.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] There are five roundabouts north of the Stirling corner junction in Barnet: Biggleswade south, Biggleswade north, Sandy A603, the ‘Black Cat’ A428/A4211, and lastly Buckden, after which there are no more roundabouts for 276 mi (444 km) until the Berwick A1167.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Black Cat roundabout is being redeveloped and is due to fully re-open in 2027.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Most of the English section of the A1 is a series of alternating sections of primary route, dual carriageway and motorway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] From Newcastle upon Tyne to Edinburgh it is a trunk road with alternating sections of dual and single carriageway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The table below summarises the road as motorway and non-motorway sections.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Most of the non-motorway sections do not have junction numbers, with the exception of the Newcastle Western Bypass which continues the junction numbering of the A1(M).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A 13-mile (21 km) section of the road in North Yorkshire, from Walshford to Dishforth, was upgraded to motorway standard in 1995.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Neolithic remains and a Roman fort were discovered.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A 13-mile (21 km) section of the road from Alconbury to Peterborough was upgraded to motorway standard at a cost of £128 million (£248 million as of 2025), which opened in 1998 requiring moving the memorial to Napoleonic prisoners buried at Norman Cross.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The total cost of these works was £50 million.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Plans to dual the single carriageway section of road north of Newcastle upon Tyne were shelved in 2006 as they were not considered a regional priority by central government.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The intention was to dual the road between Morpeth and Felton and between Adderstone and Belford.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 1999, a section of A1(M) between Bramham and Hook Moor opened to traffic along with the extension of the M1 from Leeds.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Under a DBFO contract, sections from Wetherby to Walshford and Darrington to Hook Moor were opened in 2005 and 2006.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Between September 2006 and October 2009, six roundabouts on the A1 and the A1(M) to Alconbury were replaced with grade-separated junctions.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] These provide a fully grade-separated route between the Buckden roundabout (just north of St Neots and approximately 8 miles (13 km) north of the Black Cat roundabout) and just north of Morpeth.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Upgrading the 6.2 miles (10 km) of road to dual three-lane motorway standard between the Bramham/A64 junction to north of Wetherby to meet the section of motorway at a cost of £70 million began in 2006, including a road alongside for non-motorway traffic.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The scheme's public inquiry began on 18 October 2006 and the project was designed by James Poyner.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Work began in May 2007, the motorway section opened in July 2009 and remaining work on side roads was still ongoing in late August and was expected to be completed by the end of 2009.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Upgrading of the existing dual carriageway to dual three-lane motorway standard, with a local road alongside for non-motorway traffic, between Dishforth (A1(M)/A168 junction) and Leeming Bar, began in March 2009 and opened to traffic on or about the scheduled date of 31 March 2012.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It had originally been proposed that the road would be upgraded to motorway from Dishforth to Barton (between Scotch Corner and Darlington), which was the start of current northernmost section of A1(M).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 2010 the section between Leeming and Barton was cancelled as part of government spending cuts but it was reinstated in December 2012.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Work began on 3 April 2014 and was expected to be completed by Spring 2017, but only reached completion in March 2018 due in part to significant Roman-era archaeological finds along the route of the motorway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Completion has provided a continuous motorway-standard road between Darrington (south of M62 junction) and Washington, and given the North East and North Yorkshire full motorway access to London (via the M1 at Darrington and Hook Moor).
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Councils in the north east have called for the section from Hook Moor in Yorkshire (where the M1 link road joins the A1(M)) to Washington to be renumbered as the M1.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] They maintain that this would raise the profile of the north-east and be good for business.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The same Road investment strategy announcement said that the remaining section of road between Birtley and Coal House will also be widened to three lanes each way, alongside the replacement of the Allerdene Bridge.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A modified scheme commenced in August 2014 and was open to traffic in June 2016.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The road is now three lanes each way with lane 3 narrower than lanes 1 and 2 so that all existing bridges remained as originally built.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 around Durham, Gateshead and Newcastle has seen a number of incarnations, following routes through, to the east and to the west of both Gateshead and Newcastle.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] See A1 (Newcastle upon Tyne) for more information.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A14 Ellington to Fen Ditton scheme, also known as the Huntingdon Bypass required a redesigned interchange at Brampton.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] As a result the A1 was widened to a D3 standard from the current end of the A1(M) to the slip roads connecting directly onto the A14.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] South of the new Interchange the A1 was realigned but kept as a 2 lane dual carriageway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This scheme was meant to result in the A1 becoming the A1(M) along the upgraded sections, however the legal proceedings for this did not take place, and instead features a large amount of restrictions, similar to a motorway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This scheme was opened in December 2019.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The new junction is now complete on the A1 south of Grantham, Highways England constructed 4 new slip roads to connect the A1 Trunk Road to the new Grantham Southern Relief Road (A52) being constructed by Lincolnshire County Council.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This will create a southern entry to Grantham and also to the site known as the 'King 31 Development'.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Grade Separated Junction on the A1 was opened to traffic in December 2022.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The ongoing phase three is the Southern Quadrant Link Road (SQLR), which will complete the relief road.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In August 2025, Lincolnshire County Council said the relief road would not open in 2026; its project timeline listed full completion as projected for 2028.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 road, a key route in Great Britain, has seen several major developments in recent years.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Notably, the A1 Scotswood to North Brunton upgrade, completed in November 2022, represents a significant enhancement of the route.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This project, valued at approximately £110 million, added an additional lane in each direction between junctions 74 and 79, covering a distance of five miles.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It was expected to boost economic activity in the North East by improving access to services, businesses, and housing.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The upgrade also had a positive environmental impact, reducing carbon emissions by over 8,000 tonnes, thanks to methods such as reusing materials and employing sustainable drainage systems.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 between Junctions 65 (Birtley) & 67 (Coal House) on the Newcastle Bypass is currently being widened to a D4 cross section from the existing D2 cross section, this includes replacing the existing bridge over the East Coast Main Line.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Works started in December 2021 and are due to be completed in spring 2026.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Currently, the A1 Birtley to Coal House widening project is still ongoing.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In recent developments, a contraflow system was installed on the A1 between junctions 65 (Birtley) and 66 (Eighton Lodge) in May 2024.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This shift to a contraflow will help improve safety and reduce congestion while widening bridges and constructing new lanes.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Additionally, the project has seen the successful opening of the new Allerdene bridge for northbound traffic in September 2023.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The North Dene footbridge, designed to enhance pedestrian and cyclist journeys, is also expected to open later in 2024.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] These improvements aim to increase capacity and support the regional economy by making travel safer and more efficient.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In December 2014 a scheme was announced to dual the A428 from the A1/A421 Black Cat roundabout to Cambourne.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This would include significant works to the A1/A421 Black Cat roundabout.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The existing traffic signal controlled roundabout would be replaced with a grade-separated junction.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The new Grade Separated Junction would allow the A1 and A421 traffic to pass over each other, with a middle level roundabout connecting them together including links to local roads.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Many direct accesses on the A1 would be stopped up and diverted onto new local access roads.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The scheme started construction in late 2023, the works currently underway along the A1.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] When completed this will remove one of the last 5 roundabouts on the A1 from Sterling corner to the Berwick bypass.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The replacement of the Black Cat Roundabout as part of the A428 Black Cat to Caxton Gibbet improvements project is currently ongoing.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The £1 billion infrastructure scheme aims to significantly improve traffic flow and connectivity across the region.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The project will upgrade the Black Cat roundabout into a modern, free-flowing junction, with work set to continue until 2027.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] As of 2024, National Highways has made substantial progress, including the installation of key infrastructure such as bridges and slip roads.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Recent developments include the completion of major bridge installations, with several closures planned to accommodate large-scale construction activities, such as the installation of steel beams for the Roxton Road bridge.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The A1 continues to undergo significant improvement as part of the broader effort to modernise the UK’s transport infrastructure.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] National Highways, responsible for overseeing roadworks on motorways and major A roads, has outlined plans for continued investment in the A1 to support both local traffic and freight transport.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] These upgrades are expected to alleviate congestion, improve safety, and support the economy by enhancing the accessibility of key business and service hubs across the North East.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] These projects are part of an ongoing effort to expand the A1 from its current dual carriageway sections into full motorway status in certain areas, a development that is expected to improve traffic flow and reduce accidents.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In the "Road investment strategy" announced to Parliament by the Department for Transport and Secretary of State for Transport on 1 December 2014, planning will begin to upgrade the road in South Yorkshire to raise the last non-motorway section from Red House to Darrington to motorway standard.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Once completed, it will provide a continuous motorway-standard road between Blyth, Nottinghamshire and Washington, Tyne and Wear and will provide the North East and Yorkshire with full motorway access to London via the M1, M62 and M18.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It will also improve safety along this route, as well as creating a new corridor to the North East, and reducing congestion on the M1 around Sheffield and Leeds.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This is the only missing link of motorway on the strategic M1/M18/A1(M) route London to Washington.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The announcement then said that the road from Morpeth to Ellingham would be upgraded to dual carriageway.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The selection of the preferred route was scheduled for the year 2017, with construction due to begin in 2019.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In response to questions regarding transport in the north, Highways England stated that a new dual carriageway section between Morpeth and Felton and also that of Alnwick to Ellingham would start in 2021 with full opening in 2023.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] However in June 2022 UK government minister Grant Shapps delayed a decision about a Development Consent Order signing off on National Highways' plans until December 2022.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Measures were also announced to enhance the performance and safety of the A1 north of Ellingham to include three sections of climbing lanes, five junctions with improved right turn refuges, and better crossing facilities for pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Start of construction is scheduled for 2018.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It was then also announced that planning would begin to upgrade the Newark northern bypass to dual carriageway, and the A46 junction with the A1 will be replaced to support nearby housing growth and improve links from the A1 to Newark and Lincoln.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The DCO is due to be submitted in early 2024, with construction likely to start in 2026 if approved.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 2014, the government included a proposal to widen the Doncaster By-pass to three lanes in its "Road investment strategy", however no further announcements were made and this section of motorway remains unaltered.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 2003 a proposal for a bypass of Sandy and Beeston, Bedfordshire, was put forward as a green-lighted scheme as part of a government multi-modal study, with a cost of £67 million.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] However, the Highways Agency was unwilling to confirm the information as the study was preliminary and intended for future publication.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] In 2008 the proposal was submitted for consideration in the pre-2013/14 Regional Funding Advice 2 Programme of the East of England Development Agency.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] This plan to upgrade to smart motorway has now been cancelled.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] A strategic study will examine how to improve the safety and performance of the A1 between Peterborough and the M25, including whether to upgrade the old dual carriageway section to motorway standard.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] Some sections of the A1 have been upgraded to motorway standard.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The M25 to Stotfold section is 23 miles (37 km), and was constructed between 1962 and 1986.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The main destinations are Hatfield, Welwyn Garden City, Stevenage, and Letchworth.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Alconbury to Peterborough section is 14 miles (23 km), and opened in 1998.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Doncaster By-pass opened in 1961 and is one of the oldest sections of motorway in Britain.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] It is 15 miles (24 km) long, and runs from Blyth to Carcroft.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] The Darrington to Gateshead section was constructed between 1965 and 2018.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] There was a final exit into Micklefield Village for non-motorway traffic onto what is now the access road.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] During the first week of June 2009, Junctions 44 and 45 were renumbered 43 and 44.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] At the same time the A1/A659 Grange Moor junction became A1(M) Junction 45.
[src:a90-road/a1-road-great-britain] As a result many atlases show incorrect junction numbering for this stretch of motorway.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The **A68** is a major road in the United Kingdom, running from Darlington in England to the A720 in Edinburgh, the capital of Scotland.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] It crosses the Anglo-Scottish border at Carter Bar and is the only road to do so for some distance either way; the next major crossings are the A697 from Coldstream to Cornhill-on-Tweed in the east, and the A7 near Canonbie to the west.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The southernmost section of the A68, as it leaves Darlington, has been described as a "rustbelt".
[src:a90-road/a68-road] In January 2022 there was a proposal to widen key roundabouts in Darlington to ease traffic flow.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The road crosses the A1(M) at Copshaw Hill Interchange.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] It bypasses Bishop Auckland and runs through West Auckland, Toft Hill and Tow Law, where Durham County Council has installed a live camera so that drivers can check traffic and weather.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] It then passes Consett and Corbridge; it used to pass through the centre of the town but since 1979 has run on a bypass to the east, crossing the River Tyne over Styford Bridge.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] During the construction of the bypass, Roman burials, glass and coins were found, and some traces of Dere Street.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] To return to the previous route of the A68 it is concurrent with the A69 for 2.9 miles (4.7 km), before turning off north again.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The road passes through rural Northumberland, following the route of Dere Street for much of this stretch, which is considered highly scenic.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The A68 crosses the Scottish border at Carter Bar, then runs through the Border towns of Jedburgh, St Boswells, Earlston and Lauder before going over Soutra Hill, passing through Pathhead and by-passing Dalkeith, before terminating at Millerhill Junction on the A720.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] Until September 2008, the A68 passed through Dalkeith; the opening of a bypass removed large volumes of traffic from the town centre and led to a reduction in accidents.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The northern section is used by commuters to Edinburgh, as well as long-distance traffic.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] In August 2020 part of the road near Fala collapsed after heavy rain.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] Part of the A68 is a trunk road from the boundary with Midlothian to the border at Carter Bar, managed by BEAR Scotland for Transport Scotland.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The English section as far south as the junction with the A696 to Newcastle was previously a trunk road, but was detrunked in 2001 as part of the government's "New Deal for Trunk Roads in England" report published three years earlier.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] Along with the A696, the A68 forms an alternative route between Newcastle Upon Tyne and Edinburgh to the A1 which runs along the coast via Berwick Upon Tweed, and is the more scenic of the two.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The A68 follows the Roman Dere Street north of Corbridge, crossing Hadrian's Wall, and shares its route as far as the historic camps of Habitancum and Bremenium.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The current route across Carter Bar was proposed by John Loudon McAdam in 1828.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] It was constructed over the following decade, and featured bridges designed by James Jardine.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] The A68 was the 20th most dangerous UK road in 2017.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] In 2021, the Scottish government announced funding for safety improvements in Pathhead.
[src:a90-road/a68-road] In England, some MPs have lobbied for similar safety improvements along the road.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The **A700 road** is a short but important link skirting Edinburgh City Centre between the A8 and A7 roads.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The road begins at the West End junction at the terminus of the A8 and heads south then east comprising the streets of **Lothian Road**, Earl Grey Street, Brougham Street, Brougham Place, Melville Drive, Summerhall Place and West Preston Street.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] It ends at a crossroads where it meets the A7 and A701 roads.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The major junction along its route is at Tollcross where it meets Lauriston Place, West Tollcross and the Home Street A702 road.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] It overlaps for the length of Earl Grey Street with the A702, which diverges to the west on Fountainbridge.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The northern section of the road is a designated a Red Route on which no stopping of vehicles is permitted in order to maintain traffic flow.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The Melville Drive section is flanked to the north by The Meadows, a large public park established in the 18th century.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] At each end of Melville Drive is a pair of stone pillars topped by a lion and a unicorn.
[src:a90-road/a700-road] The pair at the eastern end were built in 1881, gifted by the publishing and printing company of Thomas Nelson; the pair at the western end were built around 1886 by Sir James Gowans.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] The **A701** is a major road in Scotland that runs from Dumfries to Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] The A701 leaves Dumfries and travels north to meet the A74(M) east of Beattock.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] It then passes beneath the A74(M) before continuing to the north-east towards Moffat and ultimately Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] The road can be an alternative to the A7 or A702 routes to Edinburgh from the A74(M) and M6.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] It is signposted as a scenic route to Edinburgh from the motorway.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] The A701 is popular with motorcyclists and passes close to the edge of the Devil's Beef Tub.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] It runs also parallel with the former Talla Railway for several miles.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] A relief road for a stretch of the A701 running between Penicuik and Edinburgh has a been proposed and is being phased.
[src:a90-road/a701-road] The decision has been contested for many years, as the bypass will form a bottle neck back into the current road, and also will cut through an important wildlife corridor, a woodland which is a Site of Special Scientific Interest.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The **A702** is a major road in Scotland, that runs from Edinburgh to St.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] John's Town of Dalry in Dumfries and Galloway.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] It includes the last section of the route from London via the West Midlands and North West England to Edinburgh, which follows the M1, M6, A74(M) and finally the A702.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The A702 begins as a minor street heading north as Ponton Street from its junction with West Tolcross, then turning east into Fountainbridge, and south into Earl Grey Street where it overlaps with the A700.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] As of 2013 it is not possible to drive this 0.3-mile (0.48 km) section continuously due to opposing one-way systems.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] It starts as a primary route at the Tollcross junction in Edinburgh, and continues south until it meets the Edinburgh City Bypass (A720) on the city's outskirts.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] In the city it is known as Home Street, Leven Street, Bruntsfield Place, Morningside Road, Comiston Road and finally Biggar Road.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] It continues in a south-westerly direction beside the Pentland Hills to Biggar, before following the Clyde Valley.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The route is a major commuter route for residents of Carlops, West Linton and Biggar who work in and around the Edinburgh area.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The road passes through the villages of Coulter and Lamington, before meeting the A73 road at a new roundabout junction, and then shortly afterwards meets junction 13 of the M74.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] From Abington, it continues as a non-primary route, via the Dalveen Pass through the Lowther Hills, before and overlapping the A76 road for 11⁄2 miles until Thornhill.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] From Thornhill, the road winds south-west still, through the village of Moniaive, until eventually reaching St.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] Here, it terminates at its junction with the A713 road.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The A702 from junction 13 of the M74 is the recommended route to Edinburgh, whereas the windier A7 road is signed as the Tourist Route to Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The route attracts a large number of lorries and heavy goods vehicles and even though it includes some reasonably straight sections suitable for overtaking it can be a slow route from the M74 to Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] One other possible route to Edinburgh for those prepared to enjoy their driving more is the A701 road via Moffat.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The stretch of the A702 between Abington and Edinburgh was formerly part of the Euroroute system, of route E32.
[src:a90-road/a702-road] The E32 also ran northwards out of Edinburgh along the A90/M90 as far as Perth.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The **A71** is a major road in Scotland linking Edinburgh with Lanarkshire and Ayrshire.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] It runs south west from Edinburgh for approximately 70 miles, through Saughton, Wilkieston and south of Livingston, Whitburn and Wishaw, then by way of Overtown, Garrion Bridge, Stonehouse, Strathaven, Darvel, Newmilns, Galston, Hurlford and Kilmarnock to Irvine on the North Ayrshire coast.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] Formerly a trunk route from the east to the west coast of Scotland it has since been downgraded to a mix of primary and secondary routes.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] From Edinburgh to Darvel, it is now a secondary route, in a poor state of repair in some places.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] But, from Darvel to Irvine, it has retained its primary route status.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The A71 almost parallels the M8 between the A720 (Edinburgh City Bypass) and the junction with the A73 at Newmains.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] It passes through the village of Wilkieston and onto the Mid Calder bypass, which leads the route to the south of Livingston.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The A71 follows a very straight course through Livingston with several grade separated junctions.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] West of Livingston, the A71 turns sharply south west, bypassing Shotts, Newmains and Wishaw then descends steeply into the Clyde Valley, over Garrion Bridge at the junction with the A72.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The A71 climbs steeply up the western side of the Clyde valley on a road which it shares for a very short section with the A72.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] This small town, at a meeting of the A71, A723 and A726, provides a link to East Kilbride and Paisley, as well as to Lanark, Hamilton and Motherwell.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The A71 then becomes a narrow and winding road across moorland, as the road ascends to the head of the Avon valley.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] At the highest point is Loudoun Hill, an ancient site of human occupation, and the road here follows the route of a minor Roman road which once linked the Clyde Valley and the coast.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The road descends into the Irvine Valley, going through the towns of Darvel and Newmilns, and bypassing Galston and then through Hurlford.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] At Darvel, the A71 becomes a primary route for the rest of its length to Irvine, and widens slightly, with a straighter alignment until its junction with the A77, south of Kilmarnock.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] The A71 remains as a dual-carriageway until its terminus in Irvine town centre.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] A crash barrier runs along the central reservation of the dual-carriageway from the A77 to the boundary with North Ayrshire at Dreghorn.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] In mid 2014, the road began to subside between Darvel and Newmilns, with the westbound lane being affected near to the entrance to Gowanbank House.
[src:a90-road/a71-road] Traffic lights were put in place while a solution was sought, however as of January 2017, a solution has been found and the traffic lights have been lifted.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] The **A772** was a major A road located in Edinburgh, Scotland.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] The A772 was originally the A7 before a major renumbering of the roads into Edinburgh and also begins there, at a junction with the A701 in the neighbourhood of Nether Liberton.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] From this junction, the A772 heads south-east through Gilmerton, a suburb of Edinburgh.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] This part is known as Gilmerton Road and has a 30 mph speed limit.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] At the edge of Gilmerton, the road becomes Drum Street, where it passes The Drum, an 18th-century country house, before reverting to Gilmerton Road.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] Approximately 0.5 miles (0.80 km) from its eastern terminus, it crosses over the Edinburgh City Bypass (A720) as a partial grade-separated junction utilizing a pair of roundabouts, where there is evidence of the junction almost having an east-facing sliproad.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] Continuing along the Gilmerton Road, the A772 has a roundabout for Dobbies Garden Centre and Edinburgh Butterfly and Insect World, and an inn.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] Shortly afterwards, the A772 meets its eastern terminus at the Gilmerton Road Roundabout with the A7 and B6392 (formerly the A68) at the community of Melville Nurseries, between Lasswade and Dalkeith.
[src:a90-road/a772-road] The B6392 continues to be called Gilmerton Road as far as the River North Esk.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The **A90 road** is a major north-to-south road in eastern Scotland, running from Edinburgh to Fraserburgh, through Dundee and Aberdeen.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] Along with the A9 and the A82 it is one of the three major north–south trunk roads connecting the Central Belt to northern destinations.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The A90 is not continuous: there is a gap between Dalmeny and Perth, but the M90 connects those two places.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The creation and development of the A90 road has to be understood in terms of the development of the economy of the North-East of Scotland, which had resulted in an increase in traffic along the route between Perth and Aberdeen.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] In recognition of this, in 1979, the British government announced that it was giving priority to the upgrading of the route to dual carriageway standard.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] It had already been decided that the trunk route between Dundee and Stonehaven, which had previously followed the same route as the railway line between the two towns, would now follow an inland route through Forfar and Laurencekirk.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The coastal route from Dundee to Stonehaven was detrunked in 1978, at the same time as the inland route was trunked.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] In 1994, it was stated that £139 million had been spent since 1979 on upgrades to the then-A90 between Perth and Aberdeen (the section between Stonehaven and Aberdeen has since become part of the A92).
[src:a90-road/a90-road] A grade-separated junction at Longforgan was opened in 1996.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The section of the A90 between Balmedie and Tipperty was upgraded to dual carriageway in 2018.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] On 3 September 2018, the former section of the A90 between Stonehaven and Blackdog was renumbered A92 in preparation for the opening of the Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route, which became the new route of the A90.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] From Edinburgh, the A90 travels west and connects to the M90 motorway bypass route that leads to the M9: however, it is only possible to travel northbound when reaching this connection.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] After connecting with the M90, it runs as a short section of A-road before turning into the M90 properly at the Queensferry Crossing.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] At Perth, beneath Kinnoull Hill, the M90 again becomes the A90, now running north east to Dundee and through the Kingsway road system.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] It then passes Forfar, Brechin and Stracathro.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The section of road previously part of the A90 was made part of the A92 and continues via Newtonhill, Portlethen, Cove Bay, the urban area of Aberdeen and the Bridge of Don before rejoining the A90 at Blackdog Junction, where the A'PRT terminates.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] Continuing north, the route crosses the Ythan Estuary near Ellon where it becomes a single carriageway, skirting Peterhead (and crossing Balmoor Bridge) on its way to Fraserburgh.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The A952 road via Mintlaw is one of Aberdeenshire's principal freight routes.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The Dundee to Aberdeen stretch of the A90 has many speed cameras.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] Previously, the 60-mile (97 km) trip from Dundee to Aberdeen along the A90 entailed over a dozen speed cameras including a majority of fixed Gatso types as well as locations used by mobile camera vans.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] These cameras were found on long fast stretches of road, and shortly before dangerous junctions, such as at the Laurencekirk junction where a 50 mph (80 km/h) speed limit is in force.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] This was introduced due to this junction's appalling safety record.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] A similar speed restriction was imposed at Forfar until two new grade-separated junctions were built, after which the restriction was lifted.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] In 2017 Average Speed Cameras were erected between Dundee and Stonehaven, with 15 per side, spaced approximately every 5 miles (8 km) for a total of 30 cameras.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] BBC News reported in January 2018 that speed limit compliance had increased from 2 in 5 to 99 in 100 drivers.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] A short stretch of the A90, from the southern terminus of the M90 to Barnton Junction (a junction with the A902), is part of Euroroute E15, which runs from Inverness to Algeciras in Spain.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The E15 continues northwards on the M90, and southwards on the A902 leading to the Edinburgh City Bypass.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The A90 ran along the coast and through Aberdeen until the city was bypassed with the opening of the Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route in 2018.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The former stretch of A90 from Stonehaven through to just north of Aberdeen is now part of the A92.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] In January 2016 the Scottish Government announced £24 million for the design and construction of a new grade-separated junction at Laurencekirk on the A90.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] Ground investigations were carried out in 2019 in preparation for upgrading the flat junction between the A90 and the A937 to a flyover after a number of deaths.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] This followed years of local campaigning.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] However, in 2021 it was announced that work had been delayed.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] The proposed flyover would require the closure of a flat crossing at Oatyhill Farm which is now the sole access point to some properties after the nearby 170-year-old Oatyhill Bridge, which crosses the Dundee–Aberdeen line, was closed to road traffic in 2020.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] However, supplementary draft Orders and an Environmental Impact Assessment Report (Addendum) was published in December 2024 to facilitate the necessary works required at Oatyhill to allow the flyover to be built.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] Dualling of the section north of Aberdeen has been subject to studies since the 1980s.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] A proposal was published in 2007 for dualling the section between Balmedie and Tipperty.
[src:a90-road/a90-road] While the Balmedie to Tipperty segment was eventually dualled as part of wider AWPR works, in 2023 the Scottish Government said it had no plans to dual the route north of Ellon.
